<h2>Aging & Cellaring</h2>

<p>Merlot's aging potential varies dramatically based on quality level and regional origin. <strong>Premium Bordeaux Right Bank wines</strong> like Pétrus and Le Pin can age gracefully for 20-30 years, while high-quality Napa Valley Merlots typically peak at 10-15 years. Entry-level Merlots are best consumed within 3-5 years of vintage.</p>

<h3>Peak Drinking Windows</h3>
<p>Washington State Merlots from Columbia Valley reach their optimal drinking window between 5-12 years, when their characteristic black cherry and chocolate notes harmonize beautifully. <strong>Tuscan Merlots</strong> like Masseto hit their stride at 8-15 years, developing complex leather and tobacco undertones. California cult Merlots typically show best between 7-12 years post-vintage.</p>

<h3>Evolution Over Time</h3>
<p>Young Merlot displays vibrant plum and blackberry fruit supported by firm but approachable tannins. As it ages, the <strong>tannins polymerize and soften</strong>, while primary fruit flavors evolve into secondary notes of dried herbs, cedar, and earth. Tertiary aromas of leather, forest floor, and truffle develop after a decade. The wine's color shifts from deep purple to brick-red edges, indicating proper development.</p>

<h3>Optimal Storage Conditions</h3>
<p>Store Merlot at a consistent <strong>55-58°F with 60-70% humidity</strong>. Keep bottles horizontal to maintain cork moisture, away from vibration and UV light. Premium bottles benefit from professional cellar conditions, while everyday Merlots can age successfully in a wine refrigerator or cool basement.</p>

<h3>Aging vs. Spoilage Indicators</h3>
<p>Properly aged Merlot shows <strong>integrated tannins, complex aromatics, and balanced acidity</strong>. Warning signs of spoilage include vinegar-like aromas (volatile acidity), musty cork taint, or oxidized sherry-like notes. If sediment appears in older bottles, decant carefully—this natural precipitation indicates healthy development, not deterioration.</p>

